  "source_excerpts": [
    {
      "source": "git-inceptionlabs",
      "source_job_id": "job_4b8920cd91934505",
      "status": "completed",
      "excerpt": "Watering an orchid with an ice cube is not recommended. Orchids (especially the popular Phalaenopsis) prefer a gentle, room‑temperature soak that allows the roots to absorb moisture evenly. Ice‑cold water can shock the roots, cause temperature stress, and lead to rot.\n\nBest practice\n\nUse lukewarm water (about 20‑25 °C / 68‑77 °F).\nWater thoroughly until water drains from the pot’s bottom holes.\nLet excess water drain completely—avoid leaving the pot sitting in water.\nWater about once a week (or when the growing medium feels dry about an inch down).\n\nIf you want a slow‑release method, you can place a small, damp cotton ball or a piece of sponge in the pot, but avoid ice cubes or any very cold water."
    },
    {
      "source": "git-chatgpt",
      "source_job_id": "job_4b8920cd91934505",
      "status": "completed",
      "excerpt": "Using an ice cube to water an orchid is sometimes suggested for convenience, especially with Phalaenopsis orchids, but it’s not ideal. Here’s why:\n\nPros:\n\nSlow melting can prevent overwatering.\n\nHelps beginners avoid accidentally flooding the roots.\n\nCons:\n\nCold water can shock roots and slow growth.\n\nIce cubes may not distribute moisture evenly—roots might dry out in spots while others stay too wet.\n\nRepeated cold exposure can stress the plant.\n\nBetter approach: Room-temperature water poured slowly over the potting medium until it drains out is safer and more effective for orchid health.\n\nIf you want, I can give a simple, foolproof orchid watering routine that avoids both over- and under-watering. Do you want that?"
    },
    {
      "source": "git-grok",
      "source_job_id": "job_4b8920cd91934505",
      "status": "failed",
      "excerpt": "Error: Router stage execution failed."
    },
    {
      "source": "git-qwen",
      "source_job_id": "job_4b8920cd91934505",
      "status": "completed",
      "excerpt": "Short answer: Yes, for Phalaenopsis (moth) orchids, watering with ice cubes is generally safe and effective when done correctly.\nThe method:\nPlace 3 ice cubes on top of the potting media once a week \nwww.bhg.com\n.\nAvoid direct contact with leaves or exposed aerial roots \nu.osu.edu\n.\nEmpty any water that collects in the decorative pot to prevent root rot \nu.osu.edu\n.\nWhy it works:\nResearch from Ohio State University and the University of Georgia found Phalaenopsis orchids watered with ice cubes showed equivalent flower longevity, leaf health, and root health compared to those watered with room-temperature water \nu.osu.edu\n.\nThe slow melt helps water absorb into bark media more evenly and reduces the risk of overwatering \nwww.bhg.com\n.\nMedia temperature briefly drops to ~51–56°F during melting—well above the ~20°F threshold that would damage orchid roots \nu.osu.edu\n.\nImportant caveats:\nThis method is primarily validated for Phalaenopsis orchids grown in bark media; other orchid types may have different needs \nwww.gardeningknowhow.com\n.\nIf your orchid shows wrinkled leaves or silvery (dry) roots, it may need slightly more water; adjust accordingly \nu.osu.edu\n.\nMany orchid experts stil"
    },
    {
      "source": "git-perplexity",
      "source_job_id": "job_4b8920cd91934505",
      "status": "completed",
      "excerpt": "What to watch: Make sure your orchid is a Phalaenopsis-type (the most common for ice watering) and that the media drains well. If you see soggy media or yellowing roots, switch back to room-temperature water or adjust frequency."
    }
  ]
}

